    <node id=" Wales and the WJEC yesterday. What was most important to them was that I made an early decision and I did not equivocate on what would happen for the exams. I was able to make an informal decision at that meeting, and then, of course, there is a formal process that we have to go through. That, now, allows Qualifications Wales and the exam board to operationalise that decision, and they will be communicating with schools as quickly as possible about what schools will need to do to ensure that the systems that they will now put in place can work. We are trying, as far as we can, as I understand it, to be able to mirror as closely as possible the usual results day, for instance. It might not be possible, because, of course, we're dealing with a situation that requires human beings to be involved in it, and those human beings could find themselves unwell. So, our best attempts will be to maintain the normal rhythm of an exams day in August, but that has to be caveated by the fact that we're dealing with difficult circumstances. But, the WJEC and Qualifications Wales will be making urgent communications to exam centres to explain what will need to happen next.&#10;Speaker: Lynne" />
    <node id="1. The Welsh Government is considering several measures to support the mental health and well-being of students and staff during school closures. These include regular check-ins by school well-being staff, such as phone or FaceTime calls, to keep in touch with students.&#10;2. They also plan on promoting various online platforms that can provide mental health support, like the Meic website, and formal NHS counselling services.&#10;3. However, there is no clear guidance yet on how the process of evaluating referrals for additional learning needs pupils will continue once the situation improves. The Education Minister, Kirsty Williams AM, acknowledged the need to check on this matter and ensure that false assurances are not given if the situation on the ground does not allow for a normal evaluation process.&#10;4. Teachers have been given significant discretion in determining which children are vulnerable and eligible for support during school closures. The Welsh Government has stated that they will not put any constraints on teachers trying to identify and support vulnerable children.&#10;5. There is a potential trend for fewer schools to open and operate long-term as a response to the COVID-19 pandemic, with local authorities determining the most pragmatic use of resources. Schools may reopen after deep-cleaning if there is a confirmed case of COVID-19.&#10;6. The Welsh Government is committed to providing continuity of funding for Cylch Meithrin and other childcare settings, even if they are not able to operate as usual, to ensure these essential services can continue their work once the current situation has been resolved." />
