    <node id="1. The modulated arrangement across the UK, as mentioned by Lynne Neagle AM, aims to maintain standards and ensure confidence in the awarded grades for qualifications. This arrangement will be discussed among Qualifications Wales and their counterparts across the UK.&#10;2. To address concerns about potential bias in teacher assessments, particularly regarding black and minority ethnic children, children from the working class, and students of all genders, the modulated arrangement will need to consider these factors when determining grades. This could involve implementing measures to mitigate bias, providing clear guidelines for teachers on how to assess students fairly, or using additional methods to verify the awarded grades.&#10;3. By working together across UK jurisdictions, education officials can share best practices and develop a comprehensive approach to ensure fairness in teacher assessments. This collaboration will help maintain confidence in qualifications by demonstrating a commitment to upholding rigorous standards and addressing potential sources of bias.&#10;4. It is essential to recognize that the current situation may exacerbate existing disparities, as highlighted by Helen Mary Jones AM regarding the National Union of Students' concerns about underperformance among certain demographic groups. The modulated arrangement must take these challenges into account to ensure a fair and accurate grading process for all students.&#10;5. The involvement of Qualifications Wales and the WJEC in designing and implementing this modulated arrangement will be crucial, as they are responsible for overseeing the assessment and grading process. As Kirsty Williams AM stated, she has confidence that these organizations will develop a fair and equitable approach to determining grades while respecting their professional autonomy and expertise." />
    <node id=" We’re starting from a better base than simply having none of that externally-verified data. What will also be important is that these children have confidence in those qualifications, and so we will be looking at a modulated arrangement within Wales, and I know that Qualifications Wales are discussing with their counterparts across the UK a modulated system across the UK. So, actually, we can make sure that our standards are maintained by actually having that modulation across the UK. So, we know that those children never have to worry about the rigour that has gone into determining that grade. So, they can have real confidence.&#10;Speaker: Lynne Neagle AM&#10;Content: Okay. Helen Mary.&#10;Speaker: Helen Mary Jones AM&#10;Content: Thank you. A supplementary question that might feed into that moderation. You'll know that the National Union of Students has suggested that black and minority ethnic children and children from the working class, on the whole, don't do as well, in terms of their assessment by their own teachers. I don't know what their evidence is for that. We also know, of course, that boys tend to do better in exams, and girls tend to do better at coursework, for whatever reason that is. So," />
