    <node id="y Williams AM&#10;Content: We're using all of our platforms of communication to get these messages across. So, we're using the more informal methods of communication, but are relying on a systematic approach via individual directors and through to individual schools. Welsh Government already has a dedicated website page with all of the relevant information about coronavirus. We're looking, as quickly as we can, to have a frequently asked education questions page that we can update. Understandably, people are communicating to us on Twitter asking questions. It is impossible for the communications team here to be able to respond individually to every single person that is sending Facebook messages and sending tweets, so the best way we can do that is to collate the types of questions people are asking and then to be able to have a frequently updated question and answer page to try to respond to that. With regard to parents, for instance, we're aware of schools that have already sent a questionnaire out last night to parents saying, 'Do you consider yourself to be a key worker? Do you work in the NHS? Please let us know by tomorrow so we can put arrangements in place for your children.' So, schools are already taking the initiative and having those conversations with parents about what their needs will be. And, as" />
    <node id="1. The Education Minister, Kirsty Williams AM, stated that if teachers have an instinct that certain students are at risk or vulnerable, they should be allowed to include them in the special provisions provided during school closures. She emphasized that headteachers and teachers know their pupils best and encouraged them to use their professional judgment to identify children who may not be formally identified as at-risk but would still benefit from additional support.&#10;2. When considering including at-risk children who may not be formally identified, the speakers mentioned the need to follow public health advice and minimize the number of children in school during closures. However, they also acknowledged that some children's safeguarding arrangements require their presence at school, and those needs must be addressed as well.&#10;3. The Welsh government has stated that they will not put any constraints on teachers trying to identify and support vulnerable children, giving headteachers and teachers significant discretion in determining eligibility for special provisions.&#10;4. Local governments are working with social services departments and individual schools to identify at-risk children, ensuring that up-to-date registers and plans are in place for their continued support during school closures." />
    <node id=" they can be, as you said, Kirsty, included as one of the—. They may not be formally identified, but if the teacher knows that they're at risk, or there is an instinct that they're at risk, they might be able to be included in children who are allowed to take advantage of this special provision you're making at this difficult time.&#10;Speaker: Kirsty Williams AM&#10;Content: We will certainly raise those issues. We have to do that in the context of what is deliverable, and we also have to do that in the context of the public health advice that we are receiving as well. One of the reasons why schools are closing is to help manage this disease. We know that the ability for school closures to make a contribution to that diminishes if we have significant children in school still. So, we will take these issues into consideration, but remembering this is part of an epidemic mitigation plan. Rob is the expert on that, not me.&#10;Speaker: Rob Orford&#10;Content: Yes, absolutely. This is a rapidly-evolving problem and the scale is something that we haven't seen in 100 years, and so we're having to evolve and iterate things as we go. Next week, I think," />
    <node id="1. Based on the information provided, it is recommended that early years and childcare settings communicate with their local authorities and relevant government departments, such as those responsible for Cylch Meithrin in Wales.&#10;2. The Welsh Government has committed to providing continuity of funding for Cylch Meithrin and other childcare settings, even if they are not able to operate as usual. This is to ensure these essential services can continue their work once the current situation has been resolved.&#10;3. Usual service-level agreements and procedures may be set aside to facilitate ongoing funding during this challenging time, but this does not mean a precedent is being established for future situations.&#10;4. Specific questions about funding for Cylch Meithrin should be directed to Julie Morgan, who is responsible for this area within the Welsh Government.&#10;5. Early years and childcare settings might also consider exploring various online platforms and resources that can help provide continuity of education for children during this period of reduced attendance. This could potentially help alleviate parental concerns about the spread of COVID-19 while maintaining some level of income for the settings." />
    <node id="1. Arrangements have been made to ensure that Education Maintenance Allowance (EMA) continues to be paid to all eligible students, regardless of the circumstances. This is part of the Welsh Government's commitment to provide continuity of funding and support for students during the transition to online learning and school closures. Additionally, the Welsh Government has indicated that any support provided from their portfolio will remain in place, ensuring students can access necessary resources and assistance during this period." />
    <node id="1. Education directors and staff at Cathays Park are working together to develop a planned set of activities for children during school closures. These activities will cater to different age ranges, from young children to those aged 16 in all-through schools. The plan will include educational, cultural, and sporting activities.&#10;2. Specific attention is being given to vulnerable children, who may be at risk in terms of education or mental health. The Welsh government has given headteachers and teachers significant discretion in identifying and supporting these children, encouraging them to use their professional judgment to include those who may not be formally identified as at-risk but would still benefit from additional support.&#10;3. Local governments are collaborating with social services departments and individual schools to identify at-risk children and ensure up-to-date registers and plans for their continued support during school closures.&#10;4. Although the process of evaluating referrals for additional learning needs pupils has been affected by the current situation, schools are expected to remain open for staff to do planning and address priority needs, such as supporting vulnerable children and those whose parents are key workers. Headteachers have discretion in this matter, with the expectation that they will build on good practices already in place and plan for delivery post-Easter.&#10;&#10;In summary, education directors and staff at Cathays Park, along with headteachers, teachers, and local governments, are developing measures to address the needs of children during school closures. These measures include tailored activities for different age ranges, special provisions for vulnerable children, and continued support for those with additional learning needs. The primary focus is on using professional judgment and existing good practices to ensure the well-being and education of all children during this challenging time." />
    <node id=" in my discussions yesterday—I spoke with all 22 directors of education, and the examples we're picking up in their work with schools is they're already ahead of the curve in working with schools. So, schools have identified the number of children with health workers. It will grow, and we will need to look at that range. Then, the third area is vulnerable children. They're vulnerable sometimes in terms of education other than at school, vulnerable in terms of mental health, and for those children, as well as having an experience that we want to be planned, some have compared it to a snow day, particularly on Monday, when you're putting something together in the short term, but it will not be a formal curriculum that those children would normally go through. So, the range of activities—some will be focused on educational activities, some will be cultural, some will be sporting, and that plan will be developed on the basis of the age range of children, which in some cases may go from extremely young children up to those at the age of 16 in our all-through schools, but there will be a planned set of activities to cater for those children. What we are doing currently—I have staff back at Cathays Park who are in touch and working with directors" />
