    <node id="1. Check-ins: The Welsh Government is considering regular check-ins by school well-being staff, such as phone or FaceTime calls, to keep in touch with students during a prolonged period of school closure. This is to ensure that students maintain some level of connection with their educational settings and support networks.&#10;&#10;2. Online Facilities: The Government plans on promoting various online platforms that can provide mental health support for students, like the Meic website. By utilizing these resources, young people will have access to mental health tools and guidance while learning from home.&#10;&#10;3. NHS Counselling Services: Formal NHS counselling services will be available for students who require more intensive mental health support during school closures. This provision ensures that students can still access professional mental health care despite not attending school in person. Although the text does not explicitly mention staff's access to NHS counselling services, it is reasonable to infer that these resources are available for both students and staff.&#10;&#10;4. Guidance on Referrals: While there is no clear guidance yet on how the process of evaluating referrals for additional learning needs pupils will continue once the situation improves, the Welsh Government acknowledges the need to address this matter and ensure that false assurances are not given if the situation on the ground does not allow for a normal evaluation process." />
    <node id="1. Yes, despite the government's directions, businesses can still face unpaid insurance claims due to insurers not considering it as a disruption to business. This issue has been problematic, as discussed in the transcript, where even with government directions, insurance companies are not paying out for disruptions to business. The government tried to address this issue before by ensuring that cancellation directions for school trips abroad came from the Foreign and Commonwealth Office rather than the Department for Education, hoping that this advice coming from the Former would make insurance kick in. However, the insurance industry is not the area of expertise of the Welsh Minister for Education, and it remains a challenge even with government directions." />
    <node id="1. The Welsh Government is utilizing various platforms of communication to disseminate information regarding the pandemic to parents, relying on both informal methods and a systematic approach through individual directors and schools. A dedicated website page has been set up with relevant information about COVID-19, and they are working on creating a frequently asked education questions page for updates.&#10;2. Schools have taken initiatives to communicate with parents about their needs by sending out questionnaires asking parents if they consider themselves key workers or work in the NHS to make arrangements for their children.&#10;3. Although the Welsh Government has not explicitly mentioned specific plans to directly communicate to parents about ensuring that at-risk children do not fall through the gaps during the pandemic, it is likely that this information will also be disseminated through existing communication channels and platforms.&#10;4. The cascading of information to schools will continue to be done through individual directors, who are expected to work in conjunction with social services directors to ensure that none of these children fall through the gaps." />
    <node id="Wales has several advantages in its examination system and qualification structures that can aid in making informed decisions about post-secondary education options for students. These advantages include:&#10;&#10;1. Externally assessed work: The Welsh examination system already includes a significant amount of externally assessed work, which can serve as a strong basis for moving forward. This is particularly beneficial because it ensures objective evaluation and comparability across students." />
    <node id=" grade that helps them to make a decision as a qualifying step into what they will do next, whether that be university, whether that be a degree apprenticeship or whether that be going into sixth form, into a college, into an apprenticeship or into some work-based learning opportunities. That's why we have to focus on those children, because for them, it is absolutely critical that we do. We are at an advantage in Wales, can I say? Because of the nature of our examination system, those students already have a lot of externally assessed work that we can use as a basis to move forward on. Because we've kept our AS-levels, we have got that data. Because we have a GCSE system—. Our year 11s, if they're doing triple science, they've already done 40 per cent of their paper, so we're very fortunate. Because of the structures that we have got in our qualification system, there is already lots and lots of externally-verified work that we can use, alongside, potentially, teacher evaluation of students as well. And I think that's really important. We’re starting from a better base than simply having none of that externally-verified data. What will also be important is that these children have confidence in" />
