    <edge source="1. According to Kirsty Williams AM, there is a potential trend for fewer schools to open and operate in the longer term as a response to the COVID-19 pandemic. Local authorities are considered best placed to understand and determine the most pragmatic use of resources available to them, which are primarily human resources.&#10;2. The discretion of headteachers regarding school operations remains, but it is expected that they will engage in planning for future scenarios rather than closing schools due to safety concerns.&#10;3. Schools may reopen after deep-cleaning if there is a confirmed case of COVID-19, following usual mechanisms arranged by Public Health Wales.&#10;4. Special schools and special education will continue to play a central role in planning, with a focus on supporting vulnerable children while also accommodating the needs of children whose parents are key workers." target="1. Based on the information provided, it is recommended that early years and childcare settings communicate with their local authorities and relevant government departments, such as those responsible for Cylch Meithrin in Wales.&#10;2. The Welsh Government has committed to providing continuity of funding for Cylch Meithrin and other childcare settings, even if they are not able to operate as usual. This is to ensure these essential services can continue their work once the current situation has been resolved.&#10;3. Usual service-level agreements and procedures may be set aside to facilitate ongoing funding during this challenging time, but this does not mean a precedent is being established for future situations.&#10;4. Specific questions about funding for Cylch Meithrin should be directed to Julie Morgan, who is responsible for this area within the Welsh Government.&#10;5. Early years and childcare settings might also consider exploring various online platforms and resources that can help provide continuity of education for children during this period of reduced attendance. This could potentially help alleviate parental concerns about the spread of COVID-19 while maintaining some level of income for the settings.">
