    <edge source="Speaker: Lynne Neagle AM&#10;Content: Good morning, everyone. Welcome to the Children, Young People and Education Committee this morning. I've received apologies for absence from Siân Gwenllian, and I'm very pleased to welcome Helen Mary Jones, who is substituting for Siân today. Can I ask whether Members want to declare any interests, please? Can I just, then, place on record that I have got a son who was about to do A-levels, so is affected by the exam decision? We'll move on, then, to our substantive item today, which is an evidence session with the Welsh Government around the impact of the coronavirus pandemic on education in Wales. I'm very pleased to welcome Kirsty Williams, Minister for Education; Steve Davies, who is director of the education directorate; Huw Morris, who is the group director, skills, higher education and lifelong learning; and Rob Orford, who is the chief scientific adviser for health. Thank you all for coming. We know that this is a really difficult and pressurised time for everyone, and we appreciate your attendance. Minister, I understand you wanted to make an opening statement today.&#10;Speaker: Kirsty Williams AM&#10;Content" target="1. The Welsh Government is utilizing various platforms of communication to disseminate information regarding the pandemic to parents, relying on both informal methods and a systematic approach through individual directors and schools. A dedicated website page has been set up with relevant information about COVID-19, and they are working on creating a frequently asked education questions page for updates.&#10;2. Schools have taken initiatives to communicate with parents about their needs by sending out questionnaires asking parents if they consider themselves key workers or work in the NHS to make arrangements for their children.&#10;3. Although the Welsh Government has not explicitly mentioned specific plans to directly communicate to parents about ensuring that at-risk children do not fall through the gaps during the pandemic, it is likely that this information will also be disseminated through existing communication channels and platforms.&#10;4. The cascading of information to schools will continue to be done through individual directors, who are expected to work in conjunction with social services directors to ensure that none of these children fall through the gaps.">
