    <edge source="Speaker: Helen Mary Jones AM&#10;Content: I think, Chair, the Minister has already answered what the—. But thinking just a little bit more broadly about the mental health and well-being of staff and learners across a range of educational settings, or, indeed, young people who can't access educational settings, what considerations are you giving to how that mental health and well-being might be supported through what is an incredibly difficult time for everyone?&#10;Speaker: Kirsty Williams AM&#10;Content: Yes, that is correct. So, our expectation would be that during a prolonged period of closure—which I think, if we're honest, we have to acknowledge is what we're looking at—we would expect school staff—well-being staff, for instance in school—to be doing check-ins—phone check-ins, potentially, or FaceTime check-ins, with students, just to keep in touch with them as we go forward. We'll be looking to promote amongst young people a range of online facilities that are available—so, for instance, Meic website—so, looking to use a variety of platforms. We do, of course, have the formal NHS counselling services. I'm concerned, of course, that for some children" target="1. The Welsh Government is considering several measures to support the mental health and well-being of students and staff during school closures. These include regular check-ins by school well-being staff, such as phone or FaceTime calls, to keep in touch with students.&#10;2. They also plan on promoting various online platforms that can provide mental health support, like the Meic website, and formal NHS counselling services.&#10;3. However, there is no clear guidance yet on how the process of evaluating referrals for additional learning needs pupils will continue once the situation improves. The Education Minister, Kirsty Williams AM, acknowledged the need to check on this matter and ensure that false assurances are not given if the situation on the ground does not allow for a normal evaluation process.&#10;4. Teachers have been given significant discretion in determining which children are vulnerable and eligible for support during school closures. The Welsh Government has stated that they will not put any constraints on teachers trying to identify and support vulnerable children.&#10;5. There is a potential trend for fewer schools to open and operate long-term as a response to the COVID-19 pandemic, with local authorities determining the most pragmatic use of resources. Schools may reopen after deep-cleaning if there is a confirmed case of COVID-19.&#10;6. The Welsh Government is committed to providing continuity of funding for Cylch Meithrin and other childcare settings, even if they are not able to operate as usual, to ensure these essential services can continue their work once the current situation has been resolved.">
