    <edge source="1. The process of evaluating referrals for additional learning needs pupils during the current situation may not continue as normal due to significant constraints on delivering business as usual in education. This is because the ability to do so has been &quot;massively compromised&quot; according to Kirsty Williams AM, the Education Minister.&#10;2. While there might be some exceptions, it is likely that the evaluation of referrals will be suspended since schools are facing closures and teachers are being directed to focus on supporting vulnerable children and those whose parents are key workers.&#10;3. No clear guidance has been provided on where the process will pick up once the situation improves. Kirsty Williams AM mentioned that she would need to check on this matter and did not want to give false assurance if the intelligence on the ground suggests that it would not be possible to continue with the normal evaluation process." target="1. The Welsh Government is considering several measures to support the mental health and well-being of students and staff during school closures. These include regular check-ins by school well-being staff, such as phone or FaceTime calls, to keep in touch with students.&#10;2. They also plan on promoting various online platforms that can provide mental health support, like the Meic website, and formal NHS counselling services.&#10;3. However, there is no clear guidance yet on how the process of evaluating referrals for additional learning needs pupils will continue once the situation improves. The Education Minister, Kirsty Williams AM, acknowledged the need to check on this matter and ensure that false assurances are not given if the situation on the ground does not allow for a normal evaluation process.&#10;4. Teachers have been given significant discretion in determining which children are vulnerable and eligible for support during school closures. The Welsh Government has stated that they will not put any constraints on teachers trying to identify and support vulnerable children.&#10;5. There is a potential trend for fewer schools to open and operate long-term as a response to the COVID-19 pandemic, with local authorities determining the most pragmatic use of resources. Schools may reopen after deep-cleaning if there is a confirmed case of COVID-19.&#10;6. The Welsh Government is committed to providing continuity of funding for Cylch Meithrin and other childcare settings, even if they are not able to operate as usual, to ensure these essential services can continue their work once the current situation has been resolved.">
