    <edge source="Yes, according to the provided text, there is an expectation that headteachers and their staff will be coming into school next week. While most schools will be closed for the majority of pupils, the Welsh Education Minister, Kirsty Williams AM, has communicated that schools should remain open for staff to do planning and respond to priority needs. Headteachers have discretion in this matter, but the rationale for closing schools is not likely to be used moving forward, as stated by Steve Davies. The expectation is for headteachers and their staff to plan for delivery post-Easter and build on good practices already in place, focusing on supporting vulnerable children and those whose parents are key workers." target="1. According to the transcript, there is an expectation that headteachers and their staff will come into school next week, as stated by Steve Davies. This expectation is due to schools remaining open for staff to do planning and respond to priority needs, especially in support of vulnerable children and those whose parents are key workers. However, the decision is left to the discretion of headteachers, and the rationale for closing schools is not likely to be used moving forward.&#10;2. Teachers will have significant discretion in determining which individual children are included as &quot;vulnerable&quot; and eligible for support during school closures. Kirsty Williams AM, the Education Minister, emphasized that teachers know their pupils best and encouraged headteachers to include children who may not be obviously in need but would still benefit from additional support. The Welsh government has stated that they will not put any constraints on teachers trying to identify and support vulnerable children.&#10;3. For qualifications affected by school closures, Qualifications Wales and the WJEC will need to provide clear communication regarding how grades will be arrived at, as parents, teachers, and students will want to know what elements will and will not be taken into consideration when awarding those grades. Homeworking could potentially count towards assessments, but further details have not been provided yet. The exact methods for considering homeworking and other elements in grade calculations are still being determined and will be communicated by Qualifications Wales and the WJEC at a later stage.">
